The nerve to quadratus femoris is a branch of the sacral plexus that provides motor innervation to specific muscles in the gluteal region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior gemellus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle receives innervation from the nerve to quadratus femoris, which originates from the L5 and S1 nerve roots. This nerve also innervates the quadratus femoris muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior gemellus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the nerve to obturator internus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObturator internus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is also innervated by the nerve to obturator internus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiriformis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the nerve to piriformis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus minimus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the superior gluteal nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The nerve to quadratus femoris innervates the quadratus femoris and inferior gemellus muscles.","The nerve to quadratus femoris arises from the sacral plexus, specifically from the L5 and S1 nerve roots.","The superior gemellus and obturator internus are innervated by the nerve to obturator internus, not the nerve to quadratus femoris."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available 